Fix flaky LinkAudio teardown crash (std::bad_function_call -> terminate).

BasicLinkAudio's constructor installs a channels-changed callback on the
Controller that captures `this` and forwards into the derived members
mCallbackMutex / mChannelsChangedCallback. The destructor tries to neutralise
it via mController.setChannelsChangedCallback([]{}), but that call posts the
reset to the Link io thread asynchronously (mIo->async) and returns
immediately. The base BasicLink (which owns and joins the io thread) is torn
down only AFTER this derived destructor returns, so there is a window in which
the io thread can run Controller::updateApiChannels() and invoke the old
forwarding lambda after the derived members have been destroyed -> calling an
empty std::function -> std::bad_function_call -> unhandled on the io thread ->
std::terminate(). On Windows this surfaces as a rare FAST_FAIL_FATAL_APP_EXIT
(0xC0000409) when a peer's channel set changes while a LinkAudio instance is
being destroyed (e.g. a still-publishing peer during engine teardown).

Make the destructor block until the io thread has both applied the no-op reset
and drained every handler queued before it. setChannelsChangedCallback() and
callOnLinkThread() post to the same FIFO io queue, so a task enqueued after the
reset is guaranteed to run after it; waiting on it closes the race.

diff --git a/include/ableton/LinkAudio.ipp b/include/ableton/LinkAudio.ipp
index 0cd9159..e0a4bd8 100644
--- a/include/ableton/LinkAudio.ipp
+++ b/include/ableton/LinkAudio.ipp
@@ -19,6 +19,7 @@
 
 #pragma once
 
+#include <future>
 #include <string>
 
 namespace ableton
@@ -40,7 +41,25 @@ inline BasicLinkAudio<Clock>::BasicLinkAudio(const double bpm, std::string name)
 template <typename Clock>
 inline BasicLinkAudio<Clock>::~BasicLinkAudio()
 {
+  // Replace the channels-changed forwarding callback (installed in the ctor,
+  // which captures `this` and touches mCallbackMutex / mChannelsChangedCallback)
+  // with a no-op, then BLOCK until the Link io thread has both applied that reset
+  // and drained every handler queued before it. setChannelsChangedCallback() and
+  // callOnLinkThread() post to the same FIFO io queue, so a task enqueued after
+  // the reset is guaranteed to run after it.
+  //
+  // Without this drain the reset is fire-and-forget: an in-flight
+  // Controller::updateApiChannels() on the io thread can invoke the forwarding
+  // lambda after the derived members below are destroyed (the base BasicLink,
+  // which owns and joins the io thread, is torn down only AFTER this derived
+  // destructor returns). That calls an empty std::function -> std::bad_function_call
+  // -> unhandled on the io thread -> std::terminate(). Observed as a flaky Windows
+  // teardown crash (FAST_FAIL_FATAL_APP_EXIT, 0xC0000409) when a peer's channels
+  // change while a LinkAudio instance is being destroyed.
+  std::promise<void> drained;
   this->mController.setChannelsChangedCallback([]() {});
+  this->mController.callOnLinkThread([&drained]() { drained.set_value(); });
+  drained.get_future().wait();
 }
 
 template <typename Clock>
